Anima is prescientmoon's custom markup language (you're reading an .anima file
right now!). 

Paragraphs constitute the simplest building block of the language. The sentences
in a paragraph are free to span across multiple source-lines, as long as there
is no empty line between them.

To demonstrate the above, this sentence exists in a new paragraph!

Anima elements (known as apparitions) are denoted by a backslash, followed by 
their name. For example, one can use \... to insert the unicode triple ellipsis 
symbol into the document.

Many apparitions require an argument. Said argument can be provided between 
curly brackets, or as any number of lines indented to the right of the 
apparition itself.

For example, one can bolden text using the \*{strong apparition}. Similarily, 
one can make text italic using the \_{emph apparition}, cross text out using the
\~{strikethrough apparition}, display text in monospace using the \~{mono 
apparition}, quote text (using unicode quote symbols!) using the \"{quote
apparition}, and render inline LaTeX using the math apparition (example:
\${x^2 + y = 0}).

Date and date-times can be displayed using the \_{date} and \_{datetime} 
apparitions respectively. For example, I was born on \date{2003-08-06}. If 
output space is limited, one can use the \_{compact} apparition inside the 
aforementioned elements in order to use their compact form, i.e. 
\date{2003-08-06 \compact}.

There's a few more inline apparitions we'll take about a bit later. Before move 
on, note that any text can be commented out by being included in the comment 
apparition, denoted by two dashes.

\-- This text will get removed from the output!

Comments can be nested, and naturally span multiple lines based on their 
indentation.

\-- This comment spans multiple lines.
  We're still inside the same comment \-- But this is a nested one!
  This will be the end of the long comment :)

\# Block elements

The page itself consists of a series of \_{block elements}. You're already 
familiar with paragraphs, which get automatically inserted by the compiler as
line breaks are encountered. 

One can introduce headings using the \\# apparition (notice that we've escaped
the apparition name by using a double backslash!). The level of the heading
can be increasing by increasing the number of # symbols after the name. Note 
that we've elided the curly brackets in the heading above (since the indentation
of the text itself was enough for the compiler to go off of).

\## This is a smaller heading!

Anima will automatically assign IDs to headings based on their textual content.
Since pointing linkns to individual headings is a pretty common occurrence, one
might often need to manually specify an ID for said heading. This can be 
accompilshed by using the \_{\\id apparition} inside the heading

\### This is an even smaller heading! \id very-small-heading

For the sake of clarity, this is how one would write the above using explicit
curly brackets:

\###{This is an even smaller heading! \id{very-small-heading-2}}

Anima can generate a table-of-contents out of the headings of the page by using
the toc apparition:

\toc

Thematic breaks can be inserted by using the --- apparition:

\---

Block-quotes can be written out by using the > apparition:

\> This paragraph will be displayed as a quote! Of course, this element is free
   to span over multiple lines (just like all the others).
  
Images can be included by making use of the img and src apparitions, like this:

\img \src https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f7/RickRoll.png
  Any text inside the img apparition's argument that is not inside the
  src apparition will be included in the image element's alt-description.

Asides are quite the customizable element. At their most basic, they look like
this:

\aside \title This is an aside
  Hello there!

One can illustrate such an aside with a character icon:

\aside \character lagrange
  \title And in that light, I find deliverance
  Hello there, I'm Lagrange :3

Long asides can be made collapsable like this:

\aside \collapse \character lagrange 
  \title And in that light, I find deliverance
  Hello there, I'm Lagrange :3 (imagine there was a lot of text here)

Last but not least, one can attach a custom ID to the aside's heading:

\aside 
  \collapse 
  \character lagrange 
  \id lagrange-heading
  \title And in that light, I find deliverance

  Hello there, I'm Lagrange :3 (imagine there was a lot of text here)

Figures can be used to add a caption to any existing element:

\figure \caption This is a random image from wikipedia
  \img \src https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f7/RickRoll.png
    Any text inside the img apparition's argument that is not inside the
    src apparition will be included in the image element's alt-description.

