Anima supports two kind of lists: inline lists and block lists. The two differ
in the kind of content they contain. Both kinds of list are unordered by
default. The following exmaple highlights how one can use inline lists, although
block lists work in pretty much the same way (by using the blist 
apparition instead)

\ilist
  \item first
  \item second

Lists can be ordered with a single apparition:

\ilist \ordered
  \item first
  \item second

Links must be defined before or after being used. For example, the definition 
below allows us to use \link{rickroll-wiki-page}:

\linkdef \id rickroll-wiki-page
  https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f7/RickRoll.png

By default, the ID of the link will be used as its label. One can override said
label using the label apparition, like so: 
  \link{rickroll-wiki-page \label Rickroll (Wikipedia Page)}

A default label can be included in the link's definition:

\linkdef \id rickroll-wiki-page-labeled
  \label Rickroll (Wikipedia Page)
  https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f7/RickRoll.png

Footnotes\fn{example-footnote} work in a similar manner (although they do not 
have labels):

\fndef \id example-footnote
  This is a footnote!

Codeblocks must reference external files:

\code \lang typescript \src example.ts

Page lists can be generated using the page-index apparition. There's currently
two ways of filtering pages:

\blist \ordered
  \item By only keeping the direct descendants of a path:
    \page-index \children posts/archive
  \item By only keeping the (possibly indirect) descendants of a path:
    \page-index \descendants posts/archive

Hidden pages are, by default, not included in the generated list. To include
them, use the hidden apparition:

\page-index \hidden \children posts/archive

The page's changelog can be written anywhere by using the "change" apparition:

\change \at 2003-08-06
